\begin_inset Formula $f\left(s^{\prime}\right)-f\left(s\right)=0$
\end_inset

 on that curve (unless 
\begin_inset Formula $f=const.$
\end_inset

).
 The claim is that, for (almost!?) any 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 there is some open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(s\right)$
\end_inset

 is one-to-one, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is invertable, i.e.
 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}$
\end_inset

 exists and is unique.
